<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-08-26T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-08-26T20:00:00-05:00" n="719" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d719">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">823.00/297: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">McMillin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-08-26T20:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">August
                                            26, 1919, 8 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received August 27, 4.43 a.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>Elections held Peruvian Republic Monday for Senators, Deputies and
                                Constitutional amendments passed off quietly. Result from interior
                                not yet received. A very light vote polled but Government candidates
                                elected placing the present Government in absolute control of
                                situation. The vote is to be held later in three remote provinces
                                which will not change the result.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">McMillin</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>